[2] USA (Colorado)
Date: Mon 3 Apr 2017 2:56 pm
Source: Denver Post [edited]
http://www.denverpost.com/2017/04/03/mumps-cases-booming-colorado/


Colorado this year [2017] is seeing a surge in mumps cases unlike any other in at least a decade, but a state Health Department official said it appears that the outbreak responsible for most of the cases so far is ending.

In only 3 months of 2017, Colorado has seen 60 reported cases of mumps, and more possible cases are being investigated, said Dr Lisa Miller, the state epidemiologist. That is more than 3 times the number of cases reported in the state all of last year [2016]. Every other year in the previous decade saw only single-digit case numbers.

The biggest reason for the dramatic spike this year [2017] has been an outbreak of 46 linked cases in Denver and Arapahoe County. But Miller said no new linked cases have been identified since the end of February [2017], and health officials are hopeful that vaccination clinics helped stem the outbreak.

"But we are continuing to get sporadic cases of mumps that don't turn out to be related to the outbreak," Miller said.

Those isolated cases, Miller said, are the result of a nationwide mumps boom that mirrors Colorado's own increase. This year [2017], 37 states have reported more than 1000 mumps cases, combined, and Miller said outbreaks elsewhere will likely continue to keep Colorado case numbers ticking upward.

The mumps, which causes telltale painful swelling in the glands of the cheek and jaw, is often thought of as an old-time virus. Most people born before 1957 have probably been exposed to mumps in their lifetimes. But vaccination made mumps cases much more rare.

Miller said the outbreak this year [2017] mostly occurred in unvaccinated people. Those who have been vaccinated can still catch mumps if exposed, but it is much less likely and the symptoms would be less severe.

Miller said it is possible that mumps outbreaks are cyclical and that this year's will soon be relegated to history. But she also encouraged more people to get vaccinated in order to break the cycle.

"The intervention is really very clear," she said.

