[5] USA (Kentucky, Fayette County, Lexington)
Date: Fri 7 Apr 2017
Source: Outbreak News Today [edited]
http://outbreaknewstoday.com/lexington-first-mumps-cases-2017-whooping-cough-schools-27631/


Officials with the Lexington-Fayette County Health Department have confirmed 2 mumps cases in Fayette County. These are the 1st mumps cases of the year [2017].

Mumps is a viral infection that causes painful swelling in the glands of the cheek and jaw. Other symptoms may include low-grade fever, fatigue, loss of appetite and headache, but about a 3rd of people who have the virus don't have symptoms. The virus is spread through direct contact with the respiratory droplets or saliva of an infected person. Serious complications from mumps are rare, but include meningitis and other problems.

Symptoms of mumps usually appear from 16 to 18 days after exposure. A person with mumps can spread the disease from 2 days before to 5 days after gland swelling begins, so people with mumps should stay at home until at least 5 days after the swelling starts.

Health officials say the best way to protect against mumps in by getting vaccinated.

