[6] USA (California, San Joaquin County, Stockton)
Date: Fri 7 Apr 2017 12:47 PM
Source: The Record [edited]
http://www.recordnet.com/news/20170407/mumps-outbreak-confirmed-at-pacific


A total of 2 students at University of the Pacific have confirmed cases of mumps, the 1st such cases in San Joaquin County since 2011, according to San Joaquin County Public Health Services.

Up to 7 additional suspected cases among students are being investigated, and the university is working with the health department to stop the spread of the illness.

Public health officials are recommending that even fully vaccinated students get another dose of the measles-mumps-rubella vaccine for added protection.

"We're recommending that 3rd dose to try to stop the spread of the disease," Dr Julie Vaishampayan, assistant health officer, said in a statement. "It does help if high numbers of students take that 3rd dose."

Students who have never had the vaccine, and even those who have had only 1 dose, are even more exposed and should also be vaccinated.

The university is working with the student body to ensure access to the vaccine.

"Our priority is to ensure that the students are taken care of and that faculty, staff and the Pacific community take measures to protect themselves," said Pacific's Vice President for Student Life Patrick Day.

The 1st student with symptoms had traveled to an out-of-state conference in mid-February and developed symptoms in early March [2017]. Since late March, 2 students with close contacts to the initial student have been diagnosed with mumps, and several others have developed symptoms of inflammation of the parotid gland.

All the affected students are in the physical therapy and pharmacy programs. Students in the physician assistant program at the Sacramento campus who take some classes in pharmacy in Stockton are also being notified of possible exposure.

